<div class="landing-section">
  <h2>How it works</h2>
  <p class="subtitle">Fleet is architecturally a Map-Reduce system for software development.</p>

  <div class="diagram">
    <div><span class="label">Your laptop (commander)</span></div>
    <div><span class="muted">    │</span></div>
    <div><span class="muted">    ├──</span> reads/writes FLEET.md on main branch</div>
    <div><span class="muted">    │</span></div>
    <div><span class="label">GitHub (message bus)</span></div>
    <div><span class="muted">    │</span></div>
    <div><span class="muted">    ├──</span> Machine B <span class="accent">→ feature/auth</span></div>
    <div><span class="muted">    ├──</span> Machine C <span class="accent">→ feature/ratelimiter</span></div>
    <div><span class="muted">    └──</span> EC2 &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span class="accent">→ feature/docs</span></div>
  </div>

  <div style="margin-top: 2rem; display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(18rem, 1fr)); gap: 1rem;">
    <div>
      <h3 style="color: #facc15;">Map</h3>
      <p style="color: #94a3b8;">Each ship independently executes its mission on its own git branch. Ships never talk to each other — only to GitHub.</p>
    </div>
    <div>
      <h3 style="color: #facc15;">Reduce</h3>
      <p style="color: #94a3b8;">The commander collects completed branches, validates them, and merges into main. No SSH. No shared filesystem.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
